    "itemType": "select_all_that_apply",
    "stem": "A nurse is teaching constipation prevention. Which actions can the nurse recommend independently? Select all that apply.",
    "choices": [
      "Encourage walking as tolerated.",
      "Offer fluids within the prescribed fluid plan.",
      "Use a stimulant laxative every day until bowel movements are regular.",
      "Encourage fiber-containing foods if not contraindicated.",
      "Reduce fluid intake if stools are hard."
    ],
    "correctAnswerIndexes": [0, 1, 3],
    "correctAnswerText": [
      "Encourage walking as tolerated.",
      "Offer fluids within the prescribed fluid plan.",
      "Encourage fiber-containing foods if not contraindicated."
    ],
    "rationale": "Walking as tolerated, fluids within the prescribed plan, and fiber-containing foods help prevent constipation without jumping straight to medication. The safest teaching starts with routine bowel habits and non-medication measures unless the provider has ordered something else.",
    "whyWrong": [
      "Daily stimulant laxative use can cause dependence or cramping and should not be the routine first teaching point without provider guidance.",
      "Hard stool usually means the client needs enough fluid if allowed, not less fluid. Always follow fluid restrictions if present."
    ],
